315":"1315","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1200":"1200","1221":"1221","1196":"1196","1218":"1218","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Derby Co., Eng":"Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom","Berkshire, England":"Berkshire, England"},"nl":{"1200–":"1200–Overleden","1200–Female":"1200–Overleden","1196–1225":"1196–1225","1221–Male":"1221–Overleden","–Male":"Overleden","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1200":"1200","1221":"1221","1196":"1196","1218":"1218","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Derby Co., Eng":"Derbyshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Berkshire, England":"Berkshire, England"},"en":{"1200–":"1200–Deceased","1200–Female":"1200–Deceased","1196–1225":"1196–1225","1221–Male":"1221–Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1200":"1200","1221":"1221","1196":"1196","1218":"1218","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Derby Co., Eng":"Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom","Berkshire, England":"Berkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Forster","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: shortened form of   Forrester  , an occupational name for someone who worked in a forest.","English: possibly a Norman French nickname or occupational name from Old French <i>forcetier</i> ‘maker of scissors or shears, cutler’. Compare   Force   and   Forse  .","German (mainly <b>Förster</b>): agent derivative of Middle High German <i>forst</i> ‘forest’, denoting someone who lived in or near a royal forest, or who worked in one (see   Forst  ). This surname is also found in France (Alsace and Lorraine). Compare   Foerster  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Foster","meanings":["English: variant of   Forster   ‘worker in a forest’.","English: perhaps a nickname from Middle English <i>foster</i> ‘foster parent’ (Old English <i>fōstre</i>, a derivative of <i>fōstrian</i> ‘to nourish or rear’). But other explanations are equally or more likely.","English: from Old French <i>forcetier</i> ‘maker of scissors’; see   Forster   2."]},{"name":"Forrest","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone who lived in or near a royal forest, or a metonymic occupational name for a keeper or worker in one. Middle English <i>forest</i> was not, as today, a near-synonym of <i>wood</i>, but referred specifically to a large area of woodland reserved by law for the purposes of hunting by the king and his nobles. The same applied to the European cognates, both ancient Germanic and Romance. The English word is from Middle English <i>forest</i> ‘forest’, Old French <i>forest</i>, Late Latin <i>forestis (silva)</i>. This is generally taken to be a derivative of <i>foris</i> ‘outside’; the reference was probably to woods lying outside a settlement. On the other hand, Middle High German <i>for(e)st</i> has been held to be a derivative of Old High German <i>foraha</i> ‘fir’ (see   Forster  ), with the addition of a collective suffix.","Irish: this name is also frequently attested in Ireland, where it may be a variant of   Forrestal  ."]},{"name":"Forrester","meanings":["English: occupational name from Middle English <i>forester</i> ‘officer in charge of a forest or lord's hunting ground’ (Old French <i>forestier</i>, Anglo-Norman <i>forester</i>). See   Forrest  ."]},{"name":"Fuster","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Luis, Armando, Blanca, Ricardo, Carlos, Pedro, Vicente, Alfredo, Ana, Angelina, Barbaro.","Catalan: occupational name from <i>fuster</i> ‘carpenter’.","German and Jewish: variant of   Forster   3 and 4."]},{"name":"Foerst","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Dieter, Klaus.","German (<b>Först</b>): shortened form of <b>Förster</b> or <b>Förstner</b> (see   Forster   3). Compare   Forst  ."]},{"name":"Forsmann","meanings":["North German: variant of <b>Forstmann</b>, itself a variant of <b>Förster</b> (see   Forster  )."]},{"name":"Forstner","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Alois, Gerhard, Erna, Heinz, Ignaz, Ilse, Monika.","German (also <b>Förstner</b>): variant of   Forster  .","Slovenian (also <b>Forštner</b>): topographic or occupational name for someone who lived or worked in a forest, of German origin (see above and   Forster  )."]},{"name":"Ferster","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Erwin, Kurt.","German: variant of <b>Förster</b> (see   Forster   3)."]},{"name":"Foerster","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Gerda, Hans, Kurt, Otto, Claus, Erwin, Alois, Bernd, Christoph, Detlef, Erna, Gerd.","German (<b>Förster</b>): see   Forster  ."]}]},{"name":"Anne","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Pet form of   Ann   or   Anne ."],"variants":[{"name":"Anni","meanings":["Pet form of   Ann   or   Anne ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":15,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705188,"age":24,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705189,"age":59,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705190,"age":90,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705191,"age":115,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Anne Forster was born in 1200, in Berkshire, England as the daughter of James Forster. She married John Le Stedeman in 1218. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"1200–":"1200–Surnud","1200–Female":"1200–Surnud","1196–1225":"1196–1225","1221–Male":"1221–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1200":"1200","1221":"1221","1196":"1196","1218":"1218","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Derby Co., Eng":"Derbyshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Berkshire, England":"Berkshire, England"},"fi":{"1200–":"1200–Kuollut","1200–Female":"1200–Kuollut","1196–1225":"1196–1225","1221–Male":"1221–Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1200":"1200","1221":"1221","1196":"1196","1218":"1218","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Derby Co., Eng":"Derbyshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Berkshire, England":"Berkshire, England"},"fr":{"1200–":"1200–Décédée","1200–Female":"1200–Décédée","1196–1225":"1196–1225","1221–Male":"1221–Décédé","–Male":"Décédé","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1200":"1200","1221":"1221","1196":"1196","1218":"1218","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Derby Co., Eng":"Derbyshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni",